"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The text() function in matplotlib expects the x and y coordinates to be in data coordinates by default. However, the x-coordinate provided is a string representing a date, not a numerical value. To correctly place the text, the date string needs to be converted to a datetime object and then to a matplotlib date number using the date2num function from matplotlib.dates.\",\n  \"patch\": \"16a17\\n> import matplotlib.dates as mdates\\n17c18\\n< plt.text(\\\"2013-01-05\\\", 0.5, \\\"SAMPLE\\\")\\n---\\n> date = datetime.datetime(2013, 1, 5)\\n> plt.text(mdates.date2num([date])[0], 0.5, \\\"SAMPLE\\\")\\n\"\n}"